    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-06-13T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-06-13T18:00:00-05:00" n="115"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d115">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">868.00/6–1346: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Chargé in Greece</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Rankin</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-06-13T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 13, 1946—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>730. <gloss target="#t_urtel1">Urtel</gloss> 764, June 11, noon.<note n="18"
                        xml:id="d115fn18">Not printed; it advised that Mr. Tsaldaris expected to
                        proceed to Paris shortly for a meeting with Messrs. Byrnes and Bevin, and
                        that subject to their advice, he hoped to make a 2–week trip to London and
                        Washington (868.00/6–1146).</note> Although no rooted objection to <pb
                        facs="0182" n="170" xml:id="pg_170"/> July visit to Washington by <gloss
                        target="#t_PriMin1">PriMin</gloss> and/or MinFonOff<note n="20"
                        xml:id="d115fn20">Mr. Tsaldaris was both Greek Prime Minister and Minister
                        for Foreign Affairs.</note> Dept inclined to believe in principle that
                    American public will wonder how Greece can spare such important Mins at time
                    when Greece’s domestic problems are so critical. It would be unfortunate if idea
                    became current that Mins were on junket.</p>
                <p>Knowledge of topics Mins desire to discuss would assist both Secretary and Dept
                    in weighing pros, cons and timeliness of suggested visit.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
